You are executing the /rollback skill for the Builds workspace.

## Purpose
Recover from a bad deploy quickly and safely. If something broke after deploying,
this skill identifies the last known-good version and restores it to EC2.

⚠️ This skill touches live systems. Confirm with the user before executing any step.

---

## When this skill is triggered

The user reports that something broke after a deploy — the bot crashed, behaves
incorrectly, or logs show errors that weren't there before.

---

## Step 1 — Assess the situation first

Before doing anything, gather information:

```bash
ssh rapid2 "sudo systemctl status openclaw-paper.service --no-pager -l"
ssh rapid2 "sudo journalctl -u openclaw-paper.service --no-pager -n 30"
```

Ask the user:
- "What is the symptom — bot crashed, wrong behaviour, errors in logs?"
- "When did it start — immediately after the last deploy, or gradually?"
- "Are there any open positions that need protecting?"

**DO NOT SKIP** — Do NOT proceed until you understand what's broken.

---

## Step 2 — Identify the last good version

Check git history for deploy tags:
```bash
cd "c:/Users/benja/OneDrive/Documents/Builds/Rapid2/rapid2 v1.2" && git tag --sort=-creatordate | head -10
git log --oneline -10
```

The last deploy tag (format: `deploy-YYYY-MM-DD`) marks the last known-good state.
If no deploy tags exist, use the commit before the most recent one.

Show the user:
- Last deploy tag and its commit message
- What changed since then (git diff)
- Confirm: "This is what was running before the problem started."

---

## Step 3 — Protect open positions

Before restoring files, check if the bot has open positions that need attention:

```bash
ssh rapid2 "cat /home/ubuntu/rapid2-v1.2/state/paper_state.json"
```

If positions are open on the paper bot, note them — a restart will resume from saved state,
so they should be safe. For the production bot, flag any open positions explicitly and
ask the user if they want to manually close them before rolling back.

---

## Step 4 — Execute the rollback

Stop the service first, then restore files, then restart:

```bash
# Stop the service
ssh rapid2 "sudo systemctl stop openclaw-paper.service"

# Check out the last good files locally
cd "c:/Users/benja/OneDrive/Documents/Builds/Rapid2/rapid2 v1.2"
git checkout [last-good-tag] -- paper_bot.py strategy.py bot.py

# Push the restored files to EC2
scp paper_bot.py strategy.py bot.py rapid2:/home/ubuntu/rapid2-v1.2/

# Restart the service
ssh rapid2 "sudo systemctl start openclaw-paper.service"
```

Show the user each command before running it. Get confirmation for the scp step.

---

## Step 5 — Verify recovery

```bash
sleep 4
ssh rapid2 "sudo systemctl is-active openclaw-paper.service"
ssh rapid2 "sudo journalctl -u openclaw-paper.service --no-pager -n 20"
```

Confirm to the user: "Bot is back up on the previous version" or report any remaining issues.

---

## Step 6 — Restore local working files

After a successful rollback, the local files are now at the old version.
Restore the current (broken) version so it can be fixed, not lost:

```bash
git checkout HEAD -- paper_bot.py strategy.py bot.py
```

Tell the user: "Local files restored to current version — the broken code is still here
to fix. The EC2 bot is running the previous version until you fix and re-deploy."

---

## Step 7 — Record what happened

Create a brief note for the session memory:
- What broke
- What was rolled back
- What needs fixing before the next deploy

Offer to run /decide to record the root cause if it reveals something architectural.
